This works because of the vapour pressure concept, water or any liquid boils when it's vapour pressure is equal to its surrounding pressure, as for water, to equate it's vapour pressure to atmospheric pressure, it's temp must be 100°C, that's why at higher altitudes water boils at lower temperatures like 70°C so takes longer time to cook, on contrary of this video, pressure cooker increases the surrounding pressure so the water boils at higher temps like 120°C so less time to cook, theoretically at perfect vacuum water can just boil with heat of our hands

The water will remain hot enough during that time, due to it's very high heat capacity
